John Edward: Language Skills Essential to World Citizens
Scotland's independent schools have a string of achievements of academic excellence, and this was continued in 2018 with another set of excellent exam results, which were only reinforced by individual and collective successes in sport, art, music and other community enterprises.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their pupils and parents.
Independent schools are designed to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen career, and their position as world citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a custom school curriculum, we see global languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak to someone in a language they understand, it goes to their head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart".
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when it comes to building relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year's recent test results, we can see that languages are at the top of the league tables with the highest pass rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of scholars who studied foreign languages scored higher than A.
The data, collected from SCIS's 74 member schools, showed that 72 percent of students achieved an A-level in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French, and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as essential skills that children and young adults will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages now have the same status as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK Commission for Jobs and Skills in 2014 found that of the reasons employees give for struggling to fill jobs, 17 per cent are attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more likely jobs requiring languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future with such a life-long skill.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically put a multilingual person above the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15 percent.
That is why it is so important to invest in today's children's language education.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, will equip children with a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered essential for the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare and equip children with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future holds.
It cannot be denied at this stage, in a global business environment, that languages are still extremely important for the future of the country, and therefore this must be reflected in education.
Truly, modern languages should be viewed as truly "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland's young people.
It must be done well.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
