North Korea says it will "definitely not" unilaterally disarm without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions exacerbate their distrust of the United States and that the country will certainly not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons without such qualities.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body's annual General Assembly that in the past year, North Korea has taken "meaningful goodwill measures", such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and pledging not to proliferate nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding response from the U.S"., he said.
"Without any confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances we will certainly not disarm unilaterally first".
While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization that would reward North Korea for taking gradual steps, his words seemed meaningful in that it did not unconditionally reject unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the very first summit between a US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore when Kim pledged to work for "nuclear disarmament on the Korean Peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea wants a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
"The US insists on 'destruction of nuclear weapons first' and is putting more pressure on by tightening the level of sanctions to achieve its goal in a compelling way, even objecting to the 'declaration of the end of war,'" Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream of those who are ignorant of us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions are exacerbating our mistrust".
Ri did not say anything about plans for a second Kim-Trump summit that the US leader had brought to the attention of the United Nations earlier in the week.
Rather, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If the party in this nuclear disarmament issue had been South Korea and not the United States, the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a dead end".
The tone of Ri's speech was nevertheless dramatically different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korean missiles would be aimed at the US mainland after "Mr. Evil President" Trump called Kim a "firefighter" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, lavished praise on Kim for his courage in taking steps to disarm, but he said that much work still needs to be done and that sanctions still remain until North Korea destroys nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for this, saying "It doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months".
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that: "The implementation of sanctions by the Security Council must continue diligently and without pause until we realize the complete, final, confirmed destruction of nuclear weapons".
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an effort to dry up funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the outskirts of the UN General Assembly and said afterwards that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip there did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying that progress had been made, but only hours later North Korea accused him of making "insulting demands".
In a meeting with Moon, North Korea promised to dismantle a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States takes "consistent measures".
He said Kim told him that the "consistent measures" he wants to see are security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore as well as steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on getting enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year is giving all its undergraduate students more sleep in an effort to counter the growing macho culture of studying by using caffeine-fueled "all-night sessions".
An academic has found that students at the world's top university are often uninformed about the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
'At the end of it, one girl approached me and said, 'Why are they telling me this now, in my senior year?'
She said that no one had told her how important sleep was - which surprised me,' he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was offered for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as how it improves their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students were severely sleep deprived during the week.
The hour-long course involves some interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a dormitory where students are asked to click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes, and books to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation may increase the risks of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
'We know that this will not change student behavior immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes,' Professor Czeisler added.
The culture of pride in 'study all night' still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students have meant that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Making sure you get enough good-quality sleep should be a student's "secret weapon" for avoiding stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said - even avoiding weight gain, because sleep deprivation puts the brain in a starvation mode, which keeps you hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year during his freshman year at Harvard.
He said that the course opened his eyes and inspired him to pursue a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting alarms for when to go to sleep as well as when to wake up, and be aware of the damaging effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic displays and LED lights, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm and cause you to struggle to touch the sheep.
